<DOC><DOCNO> AP881206-0002 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-12-06-88 0004EST</FILEID><FIRST>r a PM-PTL-Chronology     12-06 0572</FIRST><SECOND>PM-PTL-Chronology,0591</SECOND><HEAD>Long Road Of PTL Struggles Still To Come To An End</HEAD><HEAD>With PM-PTL, Bjt</HEAD><DATELINE>COLUMBIA, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Here is a chronology of the major events atPTL since Jim Bakker's resignation as head of the Fort Mill-basedministry and its Heritage USA Christian theme park:   March 19, 1987 _ Bakker resigns amid sex and money scandalinvolving former New York church secretary Jessica Hahn. The Rev.Jerry Falwell takes over as chairman of the board and Richard Dortchbecomes president of PTL.   May 6 _ Assemblies of God leaders defrock Bakker and Dortch.   June 12 _ PTL files for protection from creditors under Chapter11 of the U.S. Bankruptcy Code.   June 30 _ Reports surface that a federal grand jury will examinepossible wrongdoing by the Bakkers and their associates, includingwhether money raised for charity was spent for the benefit ofprivate individuals.   Oct. 8 _ Falwell, the PTL board of directors, the co-hosts of the``PTL Show'' and other top executives resign from PTL during adispute over the bankruptcy reorganization plan and fears thatBakker will be allowed to return. David Clark, a ChristianBroadcasting Network executive, becomes trustee.   Dec. 22 _ U.S. Bankruptcy Judge Rufus Reynolds approves theministry's bankruptcy plan, which divides PTL into separateministerial and for-profit entities and involves a schedule forrepaying creditors. Reynolds orders PTL and the IRS to work outtheir differences within 60 days.   Jan. 31, 1988 _ PTL sues Bakker and his chief aide, DavidTaggart, for $52 million for recovery of unwarranted compensationand funds lost through mismanagement.   April 15 _ PTL announces it will not be able to make a bankruptcypayment and that it will lay off 125 full-time employees. Reynoldsorders Clark to draw up plan for selling assets.   April 22 _ The IRS revokes PTL's tax-exempt status.   May 13 _ Charlotte sports owner George Shinn announces intentionto buy PTL and build a baseball stadium on its undeveloped land.   May 20 _ Clark resigns as PTL trustee to become president ofHeritage Ministries, the non-profit ministerial entity. FormerWinston-Salem, N.C., mayor M.C. Benton becomes the new trustee.Clark later resigns as president of Heritage Ministries.   June 7 _ Jim and Tammy Bakker return to York County fromCalifornia. They open an office for Jim and Tammy Ministries andmove into a condominium costing $1,000 a month that is paid for bysupporters.   Aug. 5 _ Benton makes tentative agreement to sell Heritage USA toCanadian businessman Peter Thomas.   Aug. 31 _ Bakker and Benton agree on terms for Bakker to buyHeritage USA, paving the way for Bakker's return as leader of PTL.   Sept. 9 _ Bakker misses deadline for $3 million deposit. Bentonsays he will no longer negotiate with Bakker.   Oct. 3 _ Lawyers for Canadian businessman Stephen Mernick, anOrthodox Jew, announce Benton will recommend Mernick as the buyer ofHeritage USA.   Nov. 3 _ U.S. Attorney Charles Alexander notifies the Bakkers andTaggart they are the subject of a grand jury investigation.   Nov. 10 _ Reynolds rules that the Bakkers and Taggart must pay$7.6 million in damages to PTL.   Nov. 16-17 _ Reynolds outlines conditions that bidders must meetto have sale approved. Neither Mernick nor Thomas meets conditions.Reynolds orders Benton to establish list of guidelines for buyers tomeet. Reynolds orders auction for Dec. 12 and hearing for Dec. 13 todecide on buyer.</TEXT></DOC>